'''Hypothyroidism''' {{IPAc-en|ˌ|h|aɪ|p|ɵ|ˈ|θ|aɪr|ɔɪ|d|ɪ|z|əm}} is a state in which the [[thyroid gland]] does not make enough [[thyroid hormone]].

[[Iodine deficiency]] is often cited as the most common cause of hypothyroidism worldwide but it can be caused by many other factors. It can result from the lack of a thyroid gland or from [[iodine-131]] treatment, and can also be associated with increased [[stress (biology)|stress]]. Severe hypothyroidism in [[infants]] can result in [[cretinism]].

A 2011 study concluded that about 8% of women over 50 and men over 65 in the UK suffer from an under-active thyroid and that as many as 100,000 of these people could benefit from treatment they are currently not receiving.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-12252813 | work=BBC News | title=100,000 Older People Missing Thyroid Treatment – Study | date=2011-01-24}}</ref>

